S Supreme Court."]},{"name":"Tofte","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik, Hjalmer, Iver, Steinar, Thora.","Scandinavian (mainly Norwegian): variant of   Toft  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William Toft married Joan de Lobstock before 1222, in Europe. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1222–1301":"1222–1301","–Male":"Surnud","before 1222":"enne 1222","1301":"1301","1222":"1222","Europe":"Europe","Plumley, Cheshire, England":"Plumley, Cheshire, England"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1222–1301":"1222–1301","–Male":"Kuollut","before 1222":"ennen vuotta 1222","1301":"1301","1222":"1222","Europe":"Europe","Plumley, Cheshire, England":"Plumley, Cheshire, England"},"fr":{"–":"Décédé","–Female":"Décédée","1222–1301":"1222–1301","–Male":"Décédé","before 1222":"avant 1222","1301":"1301","1222":"1222","Europe":"Europe","Plumley, Cheshire, England":"Plumley, Cheshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"William Toft a épousé Joan de Lobstock avant 1222, à Europe. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fille."},"de":{"–":"Verstorben","–Female":"Verstorben","1222–1301":"1222–1301","–Male":"Verstorben","before 1222":"vor 1222","1301":"1301","1222":"1222","Europe":"Europ